SIMPLE: repute
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Repute
<hw>Re*pute"</hw> <pr>(r?-p?t")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Reputed</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Reputing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>r⟦eacute⟧puter</ets>, L. <ets>reputare</ets> to count over, think
over; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>putare</ets> to count, think. See
<er>Putative</er>.]</ety> <def>To hold in thought; to account; to
estimate; to hold; to think; to reckon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wherefore are we counted as beasts, and <qex>reputed</qex> vile in
your sight?</q> <rj><qau>Job xviii. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king your father was <qex>reputed</qex> for⟦br⟧
A prince most prudent.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Repute</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Repute
<hw>Re*pute"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Character reputed or
attributed; reputation, whether good or bad; established opinion; public
estimate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He who regns⟦br⟧
Monarch in heaven, till then as one secure⟦br⟧
Sat on his throne, upheld by old <qex>repute</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Specifically: Good character or reputation; credit
or honor derived from common or public opinion; -- opposed to
<xex>disrepute</xex>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Dead stocks, which have been of
<xex>repute</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>F. Beaumont.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reputedly</ent>⟦br⟧
